  | > Are there any options to improve pasta's scalability?<br>Not really options, at the moment. We check latency using [neper](https://github.com/google/neper) in the upstream [CI](https://passt.top/passt/about/#continuous-integration) (`perf/pasta_tcp` set), but it's all single-threaded.<br>There are plans to introduce [multithreading](https://bugs.passt.top/show_bug.cgi?id=13), eventually, and much more concrete [work in progress](https://archives.passt.top/passt-dev/20240202141151.3762941-1-lvivier@redhat.com/) to support [vhost-user](https://bugs.passt.top/show_bug.cgi?id=25) for virtual machines (passt(1)), first.<br>Once vhost-user support is merged, we can start playing with multithreading for virtual machines (vhost-user supports multiple queues). That would be kind of symmetric with VDUSE for containers (see "VDUSE support for containers" in [this article](https://www.redhat.com/en/blog/introducing-vduse-software-defined-datapath-virtio)): for pasta, it could look like [this](https://passt.top/static/pasta_vduse.png).<br>I'm not excluding you could get much better results by tweaking some `#define`s in tcp.c and tap.c, though. I would start with `TAP_SEQS` and `TCP_HASH_TABLE_LOAD` \-\- or perhaps "simply" profiling with perf(1) in the `ab -c 32` case. |
  
